<p class="body">Java has a quiet reputation. The varietal — properly called Javanica — doesn't generate the competition placements or auction headlines of Geisha or the intrigue of Laurina. What it has is consistency: farms that have grown it for decades know what to expect from it, roasters who've dialed it in know how to treat it, and consumers who've developed a preference for it come back reliably.</p>

<p class="body">El Quetzal has grown washed Java in Matagalpa for over 20 years, and it remains the cornerstone of their green coffee program. The Anaerobic Java is what happens when a farm that knows its Java intimately decides to see what a different processing method does to it. The answer — dried fruit forward, dark cherry, chocolate, a cup that opens up with complexity that the washed version doesn't offer — has made it one of the most requested lots in their lineup.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Understanding <em>Anaerobic Processing</em></h2>

<p class="body"><a href="/learn/coffee-processing-methods" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none;">Coffee processing</a> — how the cherry's fruit is removed from the bean before drying — has more influence on cup character than almost any other post-harvest variable. Washed processing removes the fruit before fermentation, producing clean, origin-forward cups. Natural processing dries the whole cherry, producing fruit-forward cups with heavier body. Anaerobic processing introduces a controlled variable to both approaches: oxygen deprivation during fermentation.</p>

<p class="body">In an anaerobic fermentation, coffee cherries or depulped beans are sealed in tanks that have been purged of oxygen. The resulting environment favors different microbial activity than open-air fermentation — specifically, it allows lactic acid bacteria to dominate rather than acetic acid bacteria and yeasts. The outcome is a fermentation that produces more pronounced, consistent, and often more complex flavor compounds than traditional methods.</p>

