<p class="body">The anaerobic trend in specialty coffee began in earnest around 2017-2018, when competition baristas started winning with anaerobic-processed lots that produced cups unlike anything in the conventional processing canon. Today, anaerobic processing has moved from novelty to accepted technique — though the quality of execution varies significantly across producers.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">What Anaerobic Processing <em>Does to Java</em></h2>

<p class="body">Java varietal's baseline profile — mild sweetness, balanced acidity, pleasant florals, comfortable body — gives anaerobic processing something stable to work with. Unlike a naturally processed Ethiopian, where the fruit-forward character is already intense and anaerobic processing can push flavors into unfamiliar territory, Java under anaerobic fermentation amplifies and deepens rather than transforms.</p>

<p class="body">The result at El Quetzal: the familiar Java body is present, but overlaid with dried fruit character — dark cherry, raisin, a hint of prune — that the washed Java doesn't produce. The chocolate notes that appear at medium roast are deeper and more pronounced. The complexity opens over time in the cup, which the farm notes in their recommendation to let the coffee rest a few weeks after roasting before evaluating.</p>

