<h2 class="section-head">Roasting <em>Anaerobic Java</em></h2>

<p class="body">Anaerobic-processed coffees respond differently to heat than washed lots. The fermentation byproducts are volatile — they express dramatically at light roasts and become more muted as roast level increases. For the El Quetzal Anaerobic Java, two distinct target profiles emerge:</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Light to medium-light (City)</h3>
<p class="body">Lighter roasts emphasize the dried fruit and dark cherry character. The fermentation notes are most vivid in this range, and the cup has a brightness and complexity that distinguishes the anaerobic processing clearly from the washed counterpart. Best suited for pour-over and filter applications where the cup profile has room to express.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Medium (City+)</h3>
<p class="body">Medium roasts develop the chocolate notes into a more dominant mid-palate presence, producing a coffee with notable body and a rich, sweet finish. The fruit recedes somewhat but integrates rather than disappearing — the cup at medium roast is more cohesive and approachable for customers who find light roast anaerobic coffees too unconventional.</p>

<p class="body">Avoid pushing past medium. The distinctive characters that justify the anaerobic processing — fruit complexity, fermentation nuance — diminish rapidly as roast darkens, leaving you with an expensive dark roast that doesn't deliver on its promise.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Java Varietal: <em>The Underrated Foundation</em></h2>

<p class="body">Before the anaerobic processing conversation, there's a varietal story worth telling. Java (Javanica) is not the same as "Java coffee" — a geographic designation for coffee grown on the Indonesian island of Java. The Javanica varietal is an Arabica strain characterized by tall, narrow plant structure, large cherries, and elongated beans that experienced green buyers recognize immediately.</p>

<p class="body">At El Quetzal, Java has been the workhorse of the program for over two decades. The washed Java — floral, jasmine-forward, juicy and clean — set the standard for what Nicaraguan specialty coffee could be and built the farm's reputation with long-term green buyers. The Anaerobic Java is an experiment that validated itself: the 2023/24 anaerobic lot scored one point above the washed Java from the same harvest, confirming that the processing adds genuine value rather than novelty.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Sourcing <em>Farm-Direct</em></h2>

<p class="body">El Quetzal's Anaerobic Java is available at <a href="https://elquetzal.coffee/products/eq-anaerobic-java-green-coffee" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none;">elquetzal.coffee</a> in sample sizes through full sack quantities. The farm ships from Dupuy's Houston warehouse for US buyers. Given the experimental nature of the lot and limited production, availability varies by harvest cycle — the farm plans to increase anaerobic production to match demand, but current lots sell out seasonally.</p>

<DropWidget lotName="Anaerobic Java" />

<h2 class="section-head">Building an Anaerobic <em>Program</em></h2>

<p class="body">For roasters considering anaerobic-processed coffees as a regular program offering rather than a one-off curiosity, Java is one of the more accessible entry points. The varietal's stability means the anaerobic processing produces consistent results across lots from the same farm — less variability than anaerobic naturals from high-aromatics varietals, which can shift dramatically between harvests.</p>

<p class="body">Pairing the Anaerobic Java with the Washed Java from the same farm also makes for a compelling side-by-side education experience — for retail customers, for café staff training, and for the menu itself. Two coffees, same varietal, same farm, different processing: the comparison is genuinely instructive and gives guests a reason to try both.</p>

